# 300-firebase-functions.mdc
# Applies to: firestore.rules, functions/src/**/*

You are working with Firebase backend systems for Mini Cuadre Caja.

This is a financial / operational ERP app.
Backend integrity is critical.

==================================================
PRIMARY GOAL
==================================================

Build backend logic that is:

- secure
- deterministic
- auditable
- idempotent
- maintainable
- resistant to hostile clients

Never assume client honesty.

==================================================
SYSTEM ROLE
==================================================

Firebase components used:

- Firebase Auth
- Firestore
- Cloud Functions
- Firebase Storage
- Security Rules

Responsibilities:

Firestore:
- operational data
- state
- history
- logs

Functions:
- critical logic
- validations
- closures
- exports
- derived processing

Rules:
- access control
- write restrictions
- ownership checks

==================================================
SOURCE OF TRUTH
==================================================

Cloud truth:
- Firestore documents

Client truth:
- temporary UI state only

Do not trust:
- totals from UI
- closure calculations from app
- role claims from client payloads

==================================================
CLOUD FUNCTIONS RULES
==================================================

Use Functions for:

- cash closure generation
- financial validations
- role-sensitive operations
- sync finalization
- exports to Sheets
- PDF/report generation
- duplicate prevention
- scheduled jobs

Avoid putting critical calculations in app.

==================================================
FUNCTION DESIGN
==================================================

Prefer:

- small focused functions
- clear inputs
- typed validation
- explicit outputs
- reusable internal services

Name clearly:

- createClosure
- validateShiftState
- exportDailyReport
- syncPendingEvents

==================================================
INPUT VALIDATION
==================================================

Always validate:

- auth exists
- required fields present
- numeric ranges
- allowed enums
- document ownership
- current business state

Reject malformed input early.

==================================================
AUTHORIZATION
==================================================

Use authenticated UID from context.

Do not trust UID sent in payload.

Role checks must use trusted server data:
users/{uid}

Examples:
- only admin can override critical mismatch
- only active cashier can close own shift

==================================================
IDEMPOTENCY
==================================================

Critical financial operations must tolerate retries.

Use:
- requestId
- eventId
- processedEvents collection if needed

Prevent duplicate:
- sale posting
- closure creation
- exports

==================================================
FINANCIAL RULES
==================================================

- Historical records should not be mutated casually.
- Closures must be reproducible.
- Cash movement != accounting movement.
- Differences must be explicit.
- Rounding rules must be consistent.

==================================================
FIRESTORE WRITES
==================================================

Prefer:

- batched writes when atomic group needed
- transactions when reading then writing dependent state
- serverTimestamp() for server events

Avoid many scattered writes for one operation.

==================================================
TRANSACTION CASES
==================================================

Use transaction when:

- ensuring one active shift
- close shift once only
- increment counters safely
- validating state before commit

==================================================
DATA MODEL DISCIPLINE
==================================================

Use explicit collections.

Examples:

users/
shifts/
cash_movements/
financial_events/
closures/
logs/
sync_events/

Avoid random nested structures without reason.

==================================================
LOGGING / AUDIT
==================================================

Critical actions should log:

- uid
- role
- timestamp
- action
- entityId
- result
- relevant numbers

Do not log secrets.

==================================================
ERROR HANDLING
==================================================

Return meaningful errors:

- unauthenticated
- permission-denied
- failed-precondition
- invalid-argument
- already-exists
- internal

Do not expose internal stack traces to client.

==================================================
SECURITY RULES (FIRESTORE)
==================================================

Rules should enforce:

- auth required
- least privilege
- role-based access
- immutable finalized closures if needed
- user-specific reads where required

Rules are not optional.

==================================================
STORAGE RULES
==================================================

Protect files by path ownership / role.

Examples:

closures/*
expenses/*
users/{uid}/*

No public sensitive files by default.

==================================================
EXPORTS / INTEGRATIONS
==================================================

When exporting to Sheets or email:

- never block core closure permanently
- use retry-safe flows
- log success/failure
- separate external failures from core business success

==================================================
SCHEDULED TASKS
==================================================

Use for:

- stale shift alerts
- retry exports
- summaries
- cleanup temp files

==================================================
ANTI-PATTERNS TO AVOID
==================================================

- trusting client totals
- role from payload
- duplicate closures
- broad admin bypasses
- public sensitive storage files
- huge god function
- hidden side effects

==================================================
WHEN MODIFYING RULES
==================================================

Explain:

1. what changed
2. who gains access
3. who loses access
4. risk impact

==================================================
FINAL PRIORITY ORDER
==================================================

1. Data integrity
2. Security
3. Correctness
4. Auditability
5. Reliability
6. Performance
7. Dev speed